A primera hora de una jornada inicialmente lluviosa nos desplazamos al Sacramento National Wildlife Refuge en donde estuvimos unas dos horas recorriendo el camino que hay habilitado para visitar el humedal con coche tras pagar una tasa de 6 $. Desde un principio nos llam la atencin el elevado nmero de antidas dispersas por las distintas lminas de agua y los numerosos grupos de anseriformes que se movan por los campos perifricos al humedal. Entre las especies ms destacadas apuntar nsar nival -Snow Goose- (Chen caerulescens), nsar de Ross -Ross's Goose- (Chen rossii), pelcano norteamericano -American White Pelican- (Pelecanus erythrorhynchos), morito cariblanco -White-faced Ibis- (Plegadis chihi), cerceta colorada -Cinnamon Teal- (Anas cyanoptera), pigargo americano -Bald Eagle- (Haliaeetus leucocephalus), alcaudn americano -Loggerhead Shrike- (Lanius ludovicianus), ratona de los estuarios -Marsh Wren- (Cistothorus palustris), ratona tepetatero -Bewick's Wren- (Thryomanes bewickii) y turpial capitn -Tricolored Blackbird- (Agelaius tricolor).

This is the checklist for my party on the Monte Field portion of the Tejon Ranch 2012 Christmas Bird Count.  Party leader - Rob Hansen.  4 other party members were Rob's former College of the Sequoias students: Lisa Hampton, MaryAnn Hodge, Eric Scotton, and Jose Vera.  In the morning (from about 7:30 to 10:00 a.m.) we birded (on foot) from the "hairpin turn" at the northernmost extent of Monte Field about 0.6 mile down canyon along Tejon Creek (then back along the creek).  From about 10:15 to about 1:30 p.m. we birded about 2.3 mile round trip (on foot) along a loop that started at that same hairpin turn and extended east-southeast along the oak riparian corridor at the north edge of Monte Field.  We turned back upon reaching a small sycamore grove draped with luxuriant wild grape vines.  Then, we birded while driving to the far east end of Monte field, turned around, and were back at the Sebastian Ranch gate at 2:30 p.m.  We birded in the vicinity of Sebastian Ranch gate from 2:30 - 3:33 p.m. before heading back north to the Visalia area.  Our party hours were 3.75 hours by car and 3.75 hours on foot (for a total of 7.5 party hours).  Our party miles were 20.5 miles by car and 3.5 miles on foot (for a total of 24 party hours).

TRIP COMMENTS: This list represents all the birds seen while fly fishing and in residence at the Osprey Cabin at Goodrich Creek for three days.  We arrived at 1500 on July 19 and departed at noon on July 22.  The numbers represent the most species seen at one time or in completely different areas on the same day.  Hopefully this correctly indicates the species numbers and diversity at this incredible mountain meadow of nearly 1000 Acres.  The surrounding forest was ponderosa pine and a two needle pine (lodgepole?) at the Osprey and mixed fir/pine at the A Frame.   The elevation is approx 5000'.  It was cloudy and 65 degrees when we arrived, reached 40 or less at night and was sunny and calm and in the low 80's in the daytime for the remainder of our stay.  Great Horned Owl feathers were found but not counted.  I also thought I might have heard E.Gros, Red Crossbills and where was that creeper?
SPECIES COMMENTS: Adult soared over our cabin in the evening.  The juvenile sat in the nest tree by the bridge to the A Frame and made a lot of noise

TRIP COMMENTS: Habitat: Bass Lake & Mixed Coniferous up road to Chilkoot Campground----Hybrid Hooded Merganzer/ Goldeneye observed in a cove by "The Forks" restaurant on Bass Lake. I used an Eagle Optics spotting scope on a tripod.  The time was 4:35 p.m., so the light was fading but I observed the bird for over 35 minutes. The duck had a large crest on its head which it lowered when it dove into the water.  The head was a solid dark color with no white marks. It had a golden eye.  Its bill looked more like a Hooded Merganzer bill- long and narrow with a little downturn at the end. The bird was at least 1/4 and up to 1/3 longer in length than nearby Hooded Merganzers and about the same size as nearby Common Goldeneyes.  The bird's body rode lower in the water than the Goldeneyes.  I observed the hybrid eating shellfish (clams or snails 1inch in diameter)- it held the shellfish in its bill and moved it around a little and then swallowed them whole, shell and all!

SPECIES COMMENTS: Observed in flight. It had a mostly white based tail with a narrow, dark subterminal band. Belly and back were mostly whitish. Head was dark.  Wing lining was mottled black and white.  Remiges appeared all dark.

TRIP COMMENTS: Debi Shearwater & Ron Branson for the Pinnacles Christmas Bird Count. Access to this private ranch was made possible by Irene LaMacchia, via the Rohnert Family. We thank both Irene and the Rohnerts for this. Ron has birded this ranch since the inception of the Pinnacles CBC (founded by Debi Shearwater). This was Debi's first time on the ranch. Last year, 2011, we were not able to count on the ranch because the roads were too wet. Driving on the ranch can only occur during dry periods. The portion of the ranch that we visited consisted of a beautiful grassland valley, Gloria Valley, surrounded by oaks & gray pines, and chemise-dominated chaparral. There are several seasonal wetlands, stock ponds & larger bodies of water, some lined with vegetation, some not. Several barns & other buildings exist. In past years, Ron has found various owls inside the barns, however, we did not find any this day. We did flush a great-horned owl from an oak tree. On the lower Gloria-Camphora Road, I found one burrowing owl on count day (3 on 31 Dec). Gloria-Camphora Road has had a complete habitat change from grasslands to vineyards and ag row crops. The only remaining grasslands are those of LaMacchia Ranch and Doc's Ranch. The area is large, encompasses some riparian. It is far too large an area for only 2 people to adequately cover this gorgeous habitat. If agreeable, in the future,  the count could benefit immensely from coverage by more birders. At least 22 species of birds were found on this ranch and nowhere else in the count circle. It was 43F when we started at 1030 hrs, a beautiful, sunny day. This is a gem of a ranch.
SPECIES COMMENTS: The immature female was about a 4 year old. Ron shot an image which he says shows a blue tag on the wing, when blown up. This eagle was perched near one of the ponds. At the end of the day, we returned to the main house where Ron left his car. I spotted a mated pair of eagles at the pond near this house. They flew off, when we opened the gate & I saw them hunting (coots?) at one of the ponds. I was certain that they had a nest nearby. Sure enough, I spotted a both adults, standing on the platform of a nest they were building in a gray pine. Both birds flew off when we approached by car, accidentally scaring them. Considering the size and state of other bald eagle nests in the county, which I follow, this nest is only in the very beginning stages. I can only guess as to why that is so. Perhaps, they are an inexperienced pair. Or, perhaps, there is too much human disturbance near their chosen site. Ron and I hope to be able to monitor this nest and report on their progress or success. Undoubtedly, this is not the only bald eagle nest in the Gabilan Mountain range, as I have speculated for years about bald eagle nests there. Finally, we have some confirmation. This is fabulous news.

PINNACLES CHRISTMAS BIRD COUNT AREA= private ranch that borders Pinnacles National Monument. Permission to enter granted. Party of three: Debi Shearwater (submitting this report), Ron Branson, Al de Martini. Sunny, although cold day, with little wind. High temp was 37F. The rancher reported 17 inches of rain YTD on the ranch, while the lower area (near her home), had 7 inches of rain. With only one exception, in one small area, roads were passable in my Subaru Outback with AWD. We managed to reach all of the ponds and wetlands. We saw 3 bobcats & 2 or 3 coyotes. We stayed together as one party, and primarily birded from the vehicle. It would be possible, and perhaps, desirable, to send a party out on foot, early in the morning to do the high area woods. Songbirds were quite quiet during the hours we were there.
SPECIES COMMENTS: No evidence of the nest they were building last year in the gray pine. Ne evidence of a nest this year, although nesting, even if unsuccessful, is highly likely. Hope to pursue this in spring.

TRIP COMMENTS: Scouting trip for 2012 CBC.  Cool, cloudy with light drizzles, breezy.
SPECIES COMMENTS: While out scouting our Escondido CBC area today, we came across what is probably a fully mature adult Bald Eagle just off Bandy Canyon Road near the Santa Maria Creek bridge.  Approx. map coordinates are [33.074947,-116.97989].----This is the same tree -- probably even on the same limb -- where we had two Bald Eagles in our Escondido CBC area on 31-DEC-11, and also on 01-JAN-12.  One of those looked to be a 3d-year bird, and the other appeared to be a mature adult bird.  Sadly, however, that data is not available on the eBird range and point maps, presumably due to the chronic petulance and pedantry of the system monitors.----Please note the markedly ragged flight feathers on the left wing. It would be interesting to know if this bird also turns up at the Ramona Grasslands, which is only a few miles away by air. There was some question at least year's CBC if we were in fact counting the same BAEAs seen that day in Ramona.----***----AVISO!  Your best bet is to park at the Santa Ysabel Creek/Bandy Canyon Road trailhead and walk down the trail.  But this bird is VERY skittish. We stopped a good distance away, hoping to get off a quick photo. However, the bird still bolted. We last saw it high up and headed southeast towards Ramona.

TRIP COMMENTS: With Chris and Jeremy for Thanksgiving at Bodega Bay.  Beautiful day with low wind, clear sky and high temp 60 degrees F.  I spent the first 3 hours (high tide) on the north end of the harbor and in the dunes campground.  The late morning was spent at the Tides Wharf observing from the restaurant.  The early afternoon was spent first at Doran Beach, mostly on the harbor side and out onto the mudflat (low tide), and mid-afternoon on Bodega Head (the walk around the south part of the headland).  Then back to Tides Wharf for early Thanksgiving dinner.  As we drove south on CA 1 at 5:20 pm (already dark), a Gray Fox ran across the road in front of us at about the turnoff to Doran Beach (into the willow thicket east of the highway).  Also saw Mule Deer on the headland and Harbor Seal and California Sea Lion in the harbor.  Three whale spouts south of Bodega Head, probably Gray Whales.
SPECIES COMMENTS: First I've seen at Bodega Bay.  Flying with a fish in its talons along the east shore of the harbor with a few gulls in pursuit

Note that while eBird shows us as having birded from 7:20 a.m. to 5:06 p.m., we took 45 minutes for a drive out of the count circle during a necessary side-trip into Porterville in the morning and then we birded outside our "assigned territory" for 45 minutes during our "quest" for Yellow-bellied Sapsucker in the afternoon (from 3:30 - 4:15 p.m.).
